# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hlsl-shading
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] It was developed alongside the **Cg** (short for *C for Graphics*) shading language from Nvidia.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Early versions of the two languages were considered identical, only marketed differently.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Although Cg and HLSL share the same core syntax, some features of C were modified and new data types were added to make Cg/HLSL more suitable for programming graphics processing units.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Two main branches of the Cg/HLSL language exist: the Nvidia Cg compiler (cgc) which outputs DirectX or OpenGL and the Microsoft HLSL which outputs DirectX shaders in bytecode format.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Nvidia's cgc was deprecated in 2012, with no additional development or support available.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] HLSL shaders can enable many special effects in both 2D and 3D computer graphics.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] D3D11.3 and D3D12 introduced Shader Model 5.1 and later 6.0.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Due to technical advances in graphics hardware, some areas of 3D graphics programming have become quite complex.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] To simplify the process, new features were added to graphics cards, including the ability to modify their rendering pipelines using vertex and pixel shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] In the beginning, vertex and pixel shaders were programmed at a very low level with only the assembly language of the graphics processing unit.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Although using the assembly language gave the programmer complete control over code and flexibility, it was fairly hard to use.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] A portable, higher level language for programming the GPU was needed, so Cg was created to overcome these problems and make shader development easier.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Some of them are the same as in C, while others are especially added for GPU programming.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg also features vector and matrix data types that are based on the basic data types, such as float3 and float4x4.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Such data types are quite common when dealing with 3D graphics programming.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg also has struct and array data types, which work in a similar way to their C equivalents.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg supports a wide range of operators, including the common arithmetic operators from C, the equivalent arithmetic operators for vector and matrix data types, and the common logical operators.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg shares the basic control structures with C, like if/else, while, and for.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] It also has a similar way of defining functions.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg implements many C preprocessor directives and its macro expansion system.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg programs are built for different *shader profiles* that stand for GPUs with different capabilities.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] These profiles decide, among others, how many instructions can be in each shader, how many registers are available, and what kind of resources a shader can use.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Even if a program is correct, it might be too complex to work on a profile.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] As the number of profile and shader types cropped up, Microsoft has switched to use the term "Shader Model" to group a set of profiles found in a generation of GPUs.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg supports some of the newer profiles up to Shader Model 5.0 as well as translation to glsl or hlsl.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] GPUs listed are the hardware that first supported the given specifications.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Manufacturers generally support all lower shader models through drivers.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] As in C, Cg/HLSL features a set of functions for common tasks in GPU programming.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Some of the functions have equivalents in C, like the mathematical functions abs and sin, while others are specialized in GPU programming tasks, like the texture mapping functions tex1D and tex2D.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg/HLSL programs are merely vertex and pixel shaders, and they need supporting programs that handle the rest of the rendering process.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Cg can be used with two graphics APIs: OpenGL or DirectX.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Each has its own set of Cg functions to communicate with the Cg program, like setting the current Cg shader, passing parameters, and such tasks.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] In addition to being able to compile Cg source to assembly code, the Cg runtime also has the ability to compile shaders during execution of the supporting program.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] This allows the runtime to compile the shader using the latest optimizations available for hardware that the program is currently executing on.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] However, this technique requires that the source code for the shader be available in plain text to the compiler, allowing the user of the program to access the source-code for the shader.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Some developers view this as a major drawback of this technique.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] To avoid exposing the source code of the shader, and still maintain some of the hardware specific optimizations, the concept of profiles was developed.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Shaders can be compiled to suit different graphics hardware platforms (according to profiles).
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] When executing the supporting program, the best/most optimized shader is loaded according to its profile.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] For instance there might be a profile for a graphics card that supports complex pixel shaders, and another profile for one that supports only minimal pixel shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] The Cg dialect has only ever had one compiler, in the form of Nvidia's Cg toolkit.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Microsoft has released two compilers for HLSL.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] The original compiler was the closed-source FXC (Effect Compiler), supported until 2015.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] It was deprecated in favor of the open-source LLVM-based DXC (DirectXShaderCompiler) with support for newer HLSL features.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Both compilers generate bytecode: while the older FXC used DXBC, DXC now uses DXIL.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] The Khronos Group has also written a LLVM-based HLSL compiler, in the form of a frontend for *glslang*, their GLSL-to-SPIR_V compiler.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Support for SPIR-V means that the shaders can be cross-platform, no longer limiting them to a DirectX stack.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] This task was previously performed by source-level converters like HLSL2GLSL, but the resulting code is often bloated.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] The PlayStation Shader Language (PSSL) is based on Cg/HLSL.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] The ReshadeFX shading language is also based on Cg/HLSL.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Shaders written in ReshadeFX are compiled to OpenGL, DX, or Vulkan and injected into games to act as post-processing filters.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Khronos has since evolved *glslang* into *slang*, a shading language and compiler that is mostly source-code-compatible with HLSL.
[src:hlsl-shading/cg-programming-language] Slang can compile to textual shading languages (GLSL, MSL, CUDA, WGSL), bytecodes (D3D11, D3D12, Vulkan SPIR-V) as well as the CPU.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:hlsl-shading/geometry-shader] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] A **shading language** is a graphics programming language made for programming shader effects on the graphics processing unit (unlike other programming languages, which send instructions to the central processing unit instead).
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Because of this, shading languages are usually more 'low level' languages and usually consist of special data types like "vector", "matrix", "color" and "normal".
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Shading languages used in offline rendering tend to be close to natural language, so that no special knowledge of programming is required.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Offline rendering aims to produce maximum-quality images, at the cost of greater time and compute than real-time rendering.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The RenderMan Shading Language (RSL or SL, for short), defined in the *RenderMan Interface Specification*, is a common shading language for production-quality rendering.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] It is also one of the first shading languages ever implemented.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Houdini VEX (Vector Expressions) shading language (often abbreviated to "VEX") is closely modeled after RenderMan.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] However, its integration into a complete 3D package means that the shader writer can access the information inside the shader, a feature that is not usually available in a rendering context.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The language differences between RSL and VEX are mainly syntactic, in addition to differences regarding the names of several shadeop names.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Gelato's shading language, like Houdini's VEX, is closely modeled after RenderMan.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The differences between Gelato Shading Language and RSL are mainly syntactical — Gelato uses semicolons instead of commas to separate arguments in function definitions and a few shadeops have different names and parameters.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Open Shading Language (OSL) was developed by Sony Pictures Imageworks for use in its Autodesk Arnold Renderer.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] It is also used by Blender's Cycles render engine.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] OSL's surface and volume shaders define how surfaces or volumes scatter light in a way that allows for importance sampling; thus, it is well suited for physically-based renderers that support ray tracing and global illumination.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Shading languages for real-time rendering are now widespread.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] They provide both higher hardware abstraction and a more flexible programming model than previous paradigms, which hardcoded transformation and shading equations.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] They deliver more control and richer content with less overhead.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Shaders that are designed to be executed directly on the GPU became useful for high-throughput general processing because of their stream programming model; this led to the development of compute shaders running on similar hardware (see also: GPGPU).
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Historically, a few such languages dominated the market; they are described below.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board established the ARB assembly language in 2002 as a standard low-level instruction set for programmable graphics processors.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] High-level OpenGL shading languages often compile to ARB assembly for loading and execution.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Unlike high-level shading languages, ARB assembly does not support control flow or branching.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] However, it continues to be used when cross-GPU portability is required.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Also known as GLSL or *glslang*, this standardized shading language is meant to be used with OpenGL.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The language unifies vertex and fragment processing in a single instruction set, allowing conditional loops and branches.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] GLSL was preceded by the ARB assembly language.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The Cg language, developed by Nvidia, was designed for easy and efficient production pipeline integration.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] It features API independence and comes with many free tools to improve asset management.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Development of Cg was stopped in 2012, and the language is now deprecated.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The shader assembly language in Direct3D 8 and 9 is the main programming language for vertex and pixel shaders in Shader Model 1.0/1.1, 2.0, and 3.0.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] It is a direct representation of the intermediate shader bytecode which is passed to the graphics driver for execution.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The shader assembly language cannot be directly used to program unified Shader Model 4.0, 4.1, 5.0, and 5.1, although it retains its function as a representation of the intermediate bytecode for debug purposes.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] The High-Level Shading Language (HLSL) is a C-style shader language for DirectX 9 and higher and Xbox game consoles.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] It is related to Nvidia's Cg, but is only supported by DirectX and Xbox.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] HLSL programs are compiled into bytecode equivalent of DirectX shader assembly language.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] HLSL was introduced as an optional alternative to the shader assembly language in Direct3D 9, but became a requirement in Direct3d 10 and higher, where the shader assembly language is deprecated.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Adobe Systems added Pixel Bender as part of the Adobe Flash 10 API.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Pixel Bender could only process pixel but not 3D-vertex data.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Flash 11 introduced an entirely new 3D API called Stage3D, which uses its own shading language called Adobe Graphics Assembly Language (AGAL), which offers full 3D acceleration support.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] GPU acceleration for Pixel Bender was removed in Flash 11.8.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] AGAL is a low-level but platform-independent shading language, which can be compiled, for example, to the ARB assembly language or GLSL.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Sony announced PlayStation Shader Language (PSSL) as a shading language similar to Cg/HLSL, but specific to the PlayStation 4.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] PSSL is said to be largely compatible with the HLSL shader language from DirectX 12, but with additional features for the PS4 and PS5 platforms.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Apple has created a low-level graphics API, called Metal, which runs on most Macs made since 2012, iPhones since the 5S, and iPads since the iPad Air.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] Metal has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language (MSL), which is based on C++14 and implemented using clang and LLVM.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] MSL unifies vertex, fragment and compute processing.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] WebGPU Shading Language (WGSL) is the shader language for WebGPU.
[src:hlsl-shading/shading-language] That is, an application using the WebGPU API uses WGSL to express the programs, known as shaders, that run on the GPU.
